      "id": 1,
      "text": "Kendall Park takes its name from builder Herbert Kendall, who plotted a 1,500‑home community between 1956 and 1961.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        6
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kendall_Park%2C_New_Jersey"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "The community grew in three phases: 1956‑57 between New Road and Sand Hill, 1959 south of New Road, and 1961 north of Sand Hill.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        7
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kendall_Park%2C_New_Jersey"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "Route 27, a former Indian trail, cuts through Kendall Park, linking it to Princeton eight miles southwest.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        1
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://grokipedia.com/page/kendall_park_new_jersey"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "Kendall Park sits on elevated ground that drains north to Tenmile Run and south to Heathcote Brook, all feeding the Raritan watershed.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        14
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kendall_Park%2C_New_Jersey"
    },
